---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="FAQ" description="Frequently asked questions about Reverse GitOps, the API-first, Git-recorded platform operating model.">
  <main class="page-main">
    <div class="page-content">
      <h1 class="page-title">FAQ</h1>

      <dl class="faq-list">

        <div class="faq-item" id="what-is-reverse-gitops">
          <dt class="faq-q">What is Reverse GitOps?<a href="#what-is-reverse-gitops" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              Reverse GitOps is an API-first operating model. Instead of asking users to push YAML
              to Git directly, they express intent through a typed platform API: Kubernetes custom
              resources. A controller then writes that validated intent back into Git as a commit or
              pull request. The standard GitOps delivery pipeline (review, promotion, auditability)
              stays fully intact downstream.
            </p>
            <p>
              API-first does not mean API-only. Teams can still make changes in Git when that is the
              right interface. The point is that Git no longer has to be the only user-facing write
              path.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="why-not-git-directly">
          <dt class="faq-q">Why not just use Git directly?<a href="#why-not-git-directly" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              Git is excellent for review, history, promotion, and distribution. It is often much
              less good as the primary interface for every human or tool that wants to make a small
              change. Platform teams frequently end up building an API or UI on top of Git workflows
              anyway.
            </p>
            <p>
              Reverse GitOps makes that API a first-class part of the design. Users express intent
              through a typed Kubernetes API, and a controller writes the resulting change back to
              Git for review and delivery. Git remains available for direct changes too; Reverse
              GitOps just stops treating Git as the only acceptable interface for writing intent.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="replace-gitops">
          <dt class="faq-q">Is Reverse GitOps trying to replace GitOps?<a href="#replace-gitops" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              No. It changes the write path, not the delivery model. Git can still be where changes
              are reviewed, promoted, audited, and distributed to target environments through tools
              like Flux or Argo CD.
            </p>
            <p>
              In practice, that also means teams can still make changes directly in Git. Reverse
              GitOps is API-first, not API-only.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="source-of-truth">
          <dt class="faq-q">Is Git still the source of truth?<a href="#source-of-truth" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              It depends on which question you are asking.
            </p>
            <p>
              For user intent, the typed API is the preferred front door. For reviewable and
              promotable desired state, Git is still the durable system of record. Reverse GitOps
              does not treat the workload cluster as the place where uncontrolled edits happen. It
              treats the API as a first-class input surface and Git as the reviewed record that
              downstream delivery systems consume, whether a change started from the API or directly
              in Git.
            </p>
            <p>
              If Git and the API drift, the implementation needs to make that visible and
              predictable rather than silently allowing both to evolve independently.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="production-cluster-access">
          <dt class="faq-q">Does this mean users get access to the production cluster?<a href="#production-cluster-access" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              No. The pattern is about putting a small, focused control plane in front of Git. That
              control plane does not need to be the production workload cluster. In practice,
              separating them is often part of the point.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="kubernetes-primitives">
          <dt class="faq-q">What Kubernetes primitives does this require?<a href="#kubernetes-primitives" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              Three things: a CRD that models user intent (for example an
              <code>Application</code> or <code>Environment</code> resource), a controller that
              watches those CRDs and opens pull requests or commits to a Git repository, and a
              GitOps operator downstream (Argo CD, Flux) that deploys from that repository.
            </p>
            <p>
              The <a href="/implementations">gitops-reverser</a> project provides an open-source
              controller you can start from.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="when-to-use">
          <dt class="faq-q">When should I use this pattern?<a href="#when-to-use" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              When you want a typed, validated, RBAC-enforced API as the interface for platform
              users, but still need Git review, auditability, and promotion pipelines. It is a
              good fit for platform teams who would otherwise build a custom API or UI on top of
              their GitOps workflow. Reverse GitOps lets the Kubernetes API server do that work
              instead.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="bullshit">
          <dt class="faq-q">Isn't this bullshit?<a href="#bullshit" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              Fair question. It would absolutely be bullshit to claim that Reverse GitOps can
              take an existing GitOps setup built around Helm releases, elaborate Kustomize
              overlays, and layers of environment-specific patches, and somehow reverse that back
              into clean API intent. That is not what this is.
            </p>
            <p>
              The pattern works when you have a typed, flat API resource that represents user
              intent cleanly. A Crossplane <code>PostgreSQLInstance</code> claim or a KRO
              <code>ResourceGroup</code> is a good fit: the user writes one clean resource, the
              platform handles the complexity underneath. A tangle of Helm values files with
              conditional templating is not.
            </p>
            <p>
              Reverse GitOps is a model for designing new platform APIs, not a tool for
              reverse-engineering existing ones.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="day-2-debugging">
          <dt class="faq-q">How do I debug this on day 2?<a href="#day-2-debugging" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              You need to be able to trace the full path clearly: the intent submitted through the
              API, the Git commit or pull request that captured it, the promotion path between
              environments, and the resulting resources deployed by the GitOps system.
            </p>
            <p>
              If that trace is not easy to follow, the implementation is not good enough yet.
              Updates, deletions, and drift handling still require explicit ownership decisions, but
              the debugging path should be obvious long before those edge cases show up.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="who-is-behind-this">
          <dt class="faq-q">Who is behind this?<a href="#who-is-behind-this" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              Right now: <a href="https://koudijs.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Simon Koudijs</a>,
              consultant, trainer, and founder of <a href="https://configbutler.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ConfigButler</a>.
            </p>
            <p>
              But the concept is intentionally bigger than one company. The manifesto is open
              source, the implementations are open source, and the hope is that others will build
              on this, challenge it, and create their own implementations. If Reverse GitOps is a
              useful idea, it should not belong to anyone.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" id="open-source">
          <dt class="faq-q">Is there an open-source implementation?<a href="#open-source" class="faq-anchor">#</a></dt>
          <dd class="faq-a">
            <p>
              Yes. See the <a href="/implementations">Implementations</a> page for known
              open-source projects. The reference implementation is
              <a href="https://github.com/ConfigButler/gitops-reverser" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">gitops-reverser</a>
              by ConfigButler.
            </p>
          </dd>
        </div>

      </dl>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
